body: Hello @DorianBattivelli! You're trying to load the frames that were labeled with check_labels(); they visually have labels, but there is no data associated with them. You must navigate to the regular labeled-data/videoname folder, where you'll find the CollectedData.h5 and machinelabels.h5.

Thank you @jeylau ,
Indeed I found the CollectedData.h5 but not the machinelabels.h5 file, is that normal?
In the labeled-data/videoname folder, I find 3 types of items: png files, CollectedData.csv and CollecteData.h5 files, but no machinelabels, how could I obtain this file?
It is normal if you haven't called `deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames`before; otherwise that's a bug 😄.

Indeed I did not do it, sorry ^^; I am using now the deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames command, but when I specify the path of the video, it returns: 

"No suitable videos founds in PATH "

I path the original video from my video folder, is that right?

Even if it is a single video, pass it as a list, and make sure `videotype` also matches your video extension.
In IPython, I'd encourage you to use `?deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames` or with any other function name, it's super useful to understand what parameters do (as sometimes there are optional arguments that may be relevant).

Ok thank you, precising the vidotype fixed the problem apparently, but now it returns this: 

![Untitled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66886884/94131932-e0caf600-fe5e-11ea-9ea3-ffcd63ce2285.png)

Have you an idea of the issue here?
Yes, the video path should point to the video within the DLC project. Otherwise the code won't know where to search for data and snapshots.

Not sur to understand. The path is pointing to the DLC project ("multi_camera" is the name of my DLC project folder). The path I passed is pointing to the "videos" subfolder of the DLC folder, is that not good? In which folder should I path?

Your DLC project's name does not contain an experimenter name nor the date; I do not know how it was created it but this does not look right. And the videos subfolder indeed is spelled with an S, whereas your path points to a 'video' folder.

I see. Indeed I seen the missing S in the meantime, I tried but still the same error occurs. 
On the other hand, concerning the format of the LDC project folder name, I created the folder from the GUI, when it is requiered to precise the experimenter and the name of the project. And for the 6 projects I already created, it always created folders with this format (experimenter name and date have never been included in the title...), is there a way to change that?

I corrected it manually, but the error still appears :/

![Untitled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66886884/94136041-a2d0d080-fe64-11ea-89ee-1dfea883ae97.png)

Here my config file: 

![Untitled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66886884/94136432-386c6000-fe65-11ea-9ab1-6dcf13e882f0.png)

I think that there is an issue concerning the difference for the path for my DLC project and the path of the videos (multi_camera vs. Multicamera), I'll try to figure out trying different paths. Thank you :)

Well actually, it did not fix the bug:

![Untitled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66886884/94138286-2dff9580-fe68-11ea-8bbb-657828a5dbb5.png)

the problem could not come from the modelprefix ? 
I looked for explanation about this argument in the ?deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames command, but I did not find explanation.

Your DLC project was correctly created within the Multicamera folder in your Desktop. As said earlier, it does contain a task 'multicamera', your experimenter name and the date. I do not understand why you pulled the config out of its folder; it should normally be found in C:\Users\battivel\Desktop\Multicamera\multicamera-Dorian-2020-08-19 (which should be your project path).

I pulled it out of its folder because I was having troubles with the path for colab analysis, but I don't remember exactly what was the problem.
